  <!-- Cover -->
  <div class="cover">
    <div class="seal">TOWN OF HUBBARDSTON • EST. 1767</div>
    <h1>FY2025–2030 Strategic Framework</h1>
    <p class="sub">From crisis to capability — building sustainable municipal excellence</p>
    <p>Prepared by the Select Board and Town Administration — October 2025</p>
  </div>

  <!-- Table of Contents -->
  <div class="toc">
    <h2>Contents</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="#summary">Executive Summary</a></li>
      <li><a href="#goals">Select Board Goals</a></li>
      <li><a href="#priorities">Immediate Priorities (FY25–26)</a></li>
      <li><a href="#finance">Financial & Capital Planning</a></li>
      <li><a href="#landuse">Economic & Land Use Planning</a></li>
      <li><a href="#community">Community & Engagement</a></li>
      <li><a href="#dashboard">Tracking Progress</a></li>
      <li><a href="#closing">Closing & Next Steps</a></li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <!-- Executive Summary -->
  <section id="summary">
    <div class="head" onclick="toggle(this)"><h2>Executive Summary</h2><span class="chev">▾</span></div>
    <div class="body">
      <p>Between 2019 and 2025, Hubbardston transitioned from crisis management to steady progress. What began as a response to turnover and instability became a long-term effort to modernize operations, train staff, and connect the organization around a shared direction.</p>
      <div class="note">
        <strong>Our focus:</strong> stabilizing the core, building professional capacity, and ensuring that every improvement survives beyond any single employee or term.
      </div>
      <ul>
        <li>Systems: HubbCONNECT now supports Finance, DPW, Facilities, and the Clerk’s Office.</li>
        <li>People: Over 300 hours of professional development logged through TheHub.</li>
        <li>Structure: SOPs, cross-training, and continuity plans are active across departments.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Goals -->
  <section id="goals">
    <div class="head" onclick="toggle(this)"><h2>Select Board Goals (FY2025–2030)</h2><span class="chev">▾</span></div>
    <div class="body">
      <p>These goals form the backbone of the next five years. They are broad enough to guide decisions, but specific enough to measure progress.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Fiscal Responsibility & Transparency:</strong> Three-year planning, OPEB policy, and public dashboards.</li>
        <li><strong>Infrastructure, Facilities & Resilience:</strong> 48 Gardner Road campus, public safety funding, and ADA upgrades.</li>
        <li><strong>Workforce, Governance & Succession:</strong> Cross-training, SOP library, and leadership roundtables.</li>
        <li><strong>Community Engagement & Communication:</strong> Policy hearings, volunteer programs, and quarterly reports.</li>
        <li><strong>Economic Development & Land Use:</strong> Route 68 corridor, zoning implementation, and Lot 57 readiness.</li>
        <li><strong>Innovation & Digital Government:</strong> Reliable, in-house systems that make town services easier to manage and access.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Priorities -->
  <section id="priorities">
    <div class="head" onclick="toggle(this)"><h2>Immediate Priorities (FY2025–FY2026)</h2><span class="chev">▾</span></div>
    <div class="body">
      <h3>Stabilize Operations</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Rebuild continuity in Accounting and Inspections following staff changes.</li>
        <li>Finish onboarding modules and cross-training by December 2025.</li>
        <li>Ensure every department maintains current SOPs and emergency contacts.</li>
      </ul>
      <h3>Prepare for Long-Range Planning</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Develop the three-year financial plan with debt and capital schedules aligned.</li>
        <li>Form OPEB working group; recommendation by FY2026.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Finance -->
  <section id="finance">
    <div class="head" onclick="toggle(this)"><h2>Financial & Capital Planning</h2><span class="chev">▾</span></div>
    <div class="body">
      <p>Sound financial management remains the foundation of everything we do. The next three years will focus on linking financial forecasting, capital investment, and debt management into a single plan.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Integrate capital planning, debt schedules, and grant funding.</li>
        <li>Adopt an OPEB funding policy to manage long-term obligations.</li>
        <li>Prepare the Public Safety Complex debt exclusion for late 2026.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="note">All data will feed into the public fiscal dashboard at <strong>budget.hubbardstonma.gov</strong>.</div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Land Use -->
  <section id="landuse">
    <div class="head" onclick="toggle(this)"><h2>Economic & Land Use Planning</h2><span class="chev">▾</span></div>
    <div class="body">
      <p>Hubbardston’s future growth depends on thoughtful development that fits the community’s character. We’re focusing on readiness and partnerships that attract responsible investment.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Finalize the Route 68 Economic Opportunity Zone plan in FY26.</li>
        <li>Advance the Lot 57 cleanup and site readiness project for senior or mixed housing.</li>
        <li>Implement new zoning updates with support from the Planning Board and state programs.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Community -->
  <section id="community">
    <div class="head" onclick="toggle(this)"><h2>Community & Engagement</h2><span class="chev">▾</span></div>
    <div class="body">
      <p>Transparency and access are becoming part of our culture, not just compliance. The Town will continue quarterly public hearings and publish engagement data annually.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Launch <strong>HubbSERVE</strong> in FY26 for volunteer recruitment.</li>
        <li>Maintain public policy hearing series each quarter.</li>
        <li>Track resident participation and satisfaction through surveys.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Dashboard -->
  <section id="dashboard">
    <div class="head" onclick="toggle(this)"><h2>Tracking Progress</h2><span class="chev">▾</span></div>
    <div class="body">
      <p>Each goal area has a few clear measures reviewed quarterly and shared publicly:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Fiscal Health:</strong> Budget variance under 2%; debt &lt; 10% of revenue.</li>
        <li><strong>Facilities:</strong> 85% of projects on schedule; 100% ADA compliance by FY28.</li>
        <li><strong>Workforce:</strong> 100% SOP coverage; 20+ training hours per employee.</li>
        <li><strong>Engagement:</strong> 4 policy hearings per year; volunteer roster &gt; 50.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="note">All data will appear on the <strong>HubbDASH</strong> dashboard linked from the town website.</div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Closing -->
  <section id="closing">
    <div class="head" onclick="toggle(this)"><h2>Closing & Next Steps</h2><span class="chev">▾</span></div>
    <div class="body">
      <p><strong>Tonight:</strong> accept the draft and confirm Q2 stabilization plan.</p>
      <p><strong>October 20:</strong> adopt Select Board goals and set financial working groups.</p>
      <p><strong>Next Quarter:</strong> approve dashboard metrics and align the CIP schedule.</p>
      <div class="note">This framework is a living document. Progress will be reviewed quarterly and adjusted annually during the Select Board retreat.</div>
      <p>“This isn’t a plan on a shelf—it’s a system we use to stay accountable.”</p>
    </div>
  </section>

</div>

<script>
function toggle(head){
  const body = head.nextElementSibling;
  const chev = head.querySelector('.chev');
  const open = body.style.display !== 'none';
  body.style.display = open ? 'none' : 'block';
  chev.textContent = open ? '▸' : '▾';
}
// start expanded for presentation
document.querySelectorAll('section .body').forEach(b => b.style.display = 'block');
</script>
</body>
